3351.name: Births attended by skilled health staff (% of total)
3351.description: Births attended by skilled health staff are the percentage of deliveries attended by personnel trained to give the necessary supervision, care, and advice to women during pregnancy, labor, and the postpartum period; to conduct deliveries on their own; and to care for newborns.
3351.s_name: World Bank – WDI: Births attended by skilled health staff (% of total)

source.name: World Bank – WDI: Births attended by skilled health staff (% of total)
source.dataPublisherSource: UNICEF, State of the World's Children, Childinfo, and Demographic and Health Surveys.
source.additionalInfo:
Limitations and exceptions: For the indicators that are from household surveys, the year refers to the survey year. For more information, consult the original sources.
General comments: Assistance by trained professionals during birth reduces the incidence of maternal deaths during childbirth. The share of births attended by skilled health staff is an indicator of a health system’s ability to provide adequate care for pregnant women.
